    bio: "Abu Abdullah Muhammad ibn Battuta was born in Tangier, Morocco, into a family of Islamic legal scholars. At the age of twenty-one, he set out on the hajj to Mecca — a journey that would stretch into nearly three decades of continuous travel across the known world. By the time he returned home for good, he had traversed approximately 75,000 miles, a distance unmatched by any individual traveler until the age of steam.\n\nHis journeys carried him across North Africa, through the Middle East, down the coast of East Africa, across the steppes of Central Asia, through India where he served as a judge under the Delhi Sultanate, to Southeast Asia, and reportedly to China. He survived shipwrecks, civil wars, plague, and bandit attacks, relying on the vast network of Islamic hospitality and scholarly exchange that connected the medieval Muslim world. Everywhere he went, he observed local customs, political structures, and religious practices with a keen and often opinionated eye.\n\nUpon his final return to Morocco, Sultan Abu Inan Faris commissioned the scholar Ibn Juzayy to record Ibn Battuta's accounts. The resulting work, known as the \"Rihla\" (The Journey), stands as one of the most important travel narratives in history. Though some scholars have questioned whether he visited every place he claimed, the Rihla remains an invaluable source for understanding the medieval Islamic world at its most interconnected — a vivid testament to one man's inexhaustible curiosity and the globalizing power of faith, trade, and adventure."
